    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1583459">
      <p class="text">As a über Scandinavian (half Swedish and half Norwegian) I must mention that the lefse is the perfect hot dog bread. This is how you get your wiener served in Norway, just add mustard and ketchup (and maybe some dried onions). And also, as some of you mentioned: butter, sugar and cinnamon makes the perfect treat to a cup of coffee. Enjoy!</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/332691">Sara O</a>
            on <a href="#cid-1583459" name="cid-1583459" title="Link to this comment">08.13.12 <span>at</span> 04:34PM</a>
      </div> <!-- .footer -->
      </div>
    <div class="article comment" id="cid-1583491">
      <p class="text">This Bayridge Brooklyn Norske (yes...until about the 1960s it was Norwegian central) grew up eating these everytime we visited Grandma in Bayside. I tried to make once, and didn't have much sucess. The slightly bitter taste of the browned areas combined with butter and sugar is such a strong cultural memory. I'm going to try again!</p>
      <div class="footer meta">
            posted by
            <a href="http://community.apartmenttherapy.com/users/208586">Janice S</a>
